{{Infobox ethnic group| |group=Azawagh Arabs |image=<!-- Unsourced image removed: [[Image:Baggara Tribesman.jpg|220px]] --> |population=Numbering over 1 million |popplace= * {{flag|Algeria}}: at least 150,000 * {{flag|Mali}}: at least 210,000 * {{flag|Niger}}: at least 10,000 |langs=[[Hassaniya Arabic]] |rels=Predominantly [[Sunni Islam]] |related=[[Arabs]] ([[Bedouin|Bedouin groups]])}}
The '''Azawagh Arabs''' ({{lang-ar|أزواغ عرب}}) (also known as nomadic [[Moors]]) are nomadic [[ethnic]] [[Arabs|Arab]]-ancestry tribes who are settling mainly in the area of [[Azawagh]] which is a dry [[structural basin|basin]] covering what is today northwestern [[Niger]], as well as parts of northeastern [[Mali]] and southern [[Algeria]].<ref>Paris (1995): p. 250.</ref> Azawagh Arabs are named after the Azawagh region of the [[Sahara]].<ref>For an introduction to the culture of the ''Azawagh Arabs'', see Rebecca Popenoe, ''Feeding Desire — Fatness, Beauty and Sexuality among a Saharan People''. Routledge, London (2003) {{ISBN|0-415-28096-6}}</ref> and speak [[Hassaniya Arabic]] which is one of the regional [[varieties of Arabic]].<ref>Popenoe (2003), p. 16-17.</ref>
